#ProtectAbortionAccess did you know 8 in 10 Americans support access to legal abortion? That’s right, We’re the majority. 
Feminist Platform Social Justice Curator @aishabburrowes in community and conversation with NARAL @prochoiceamerica and @annie_wu_22 ➡️ Watch & Listen
 ✅ Learn how to continue taking action
✅ what does NARAL do ✅ about the fundraiser & how NARAL will use the donations ✅ combat disinformation ✅ why we need (WHPA) The Women’s Health Protection Act

📞Call your senators and representatives and tell them to support reproductive freedom and pass WHPA: 202-224-3121 (Capitol switchboard will connect you to the office you request)

💜Visit prochoiceamerica.org to get involved in NARAL and learn more.

‼️If you are pregnant, there are resources and people fighting for you. Visit needabortion.org to get the support in getting services and funds you need.

🙏Thank you to the Feminist community for donating 🎉  See #LinkinBio to continue supporting reproductive justice in the U.S.

#FeministPartner @chellaman’s latest project, “Big Deaf” continues to push the boundaries of what it means to be accessible, inclusive, and equal in this world. ➡️ See more at @whatthefuckisthischella.

“Unfortunately the continuum of disability is rarely taught or acknowledged leaving stereotypes as the only outline non-disabled individuals have of disability. With 15% of the world’s population being disabled, the individuality of our community should come at no surprise…” 💭 @chellaman

In this project, @chellaman reflect’s on his own deaf identity to navigate the reality of the continuum of identity. You can discover the perpetual release of “Big Deaf”  at @whatthefuckisthischella ✨

“The Beauty Within” is a short film following sisters Aaraf (@aarafxadam) and Abrar Adam (@abrawrr) on their journey to find their individuality, voice, and strength. A film by @kanxsuda
✨ We interviewed Aaraf for film release, see link in bio. 🔗  These women embody the power of Black female heroism through their vulnerability and unity. The silent interaction between these sisters showcases the power and perseverance that lies within each of us— the beauty within. The film features ballerinas Sydnie Collins and Audrey Malek performing as guiding fairies, leading the main characters through their journey of self-identity. The audio throughout is a poem written to serve as a reminder that “ Black, Indigenous and women of color must always be present, visible and amplified.” - @aarafxadam

*Credits in the Comments*

👋 Hello @Feminist Community! We are taking part in today’s #WelcomeWednesday and spotlighting Ren Fernandez-Kim, @corpusren, a member of the Feminist advisory board. 📸 @kernieflakes

Ren Fernàndez-Kim is a Korean-Peruvian nonbinary creator (she/they) who was born in Korea, raised in Louisiana, and now currently lives in Los Angeles. They approach the world from a ‘both and’ point of view rather than an ‘either or’ mindset which has allowed Ren to embrace their non-binary identity and innovate as a creator and educator. As of currently, their focus is creating safe spaces whilst also promoting education that is accessible to everyone. On @corpusren you will find they feature moments of their own growth and discovery because it’s exciting.

“I am adamant in the continuing process of education whether it’s in a classroom setting or not. Which is why I truly enjoy Anthropology and the layers that allow me to connect with people from all spaces. I love meeting people and learning something new about them. In general, the human experience is something that gives me so much joy and wonder! It expands my understandings of the world around me and I love seeing others also learn something new! It’s an adventure!” @corpusren

We encourage our community to follow and support #FeministAdvisor @corupusren

While the 2021 #MetGala guests were arriving outside the Met, a historic demonstration was taking place. 18 year old queer non-binary activist Ella (@g0lddior) chanted “By Any Means Necessary” alongside activists fighting for Black trans and Non-binary liberation. Read more below via @joelriveraa ⬇️ share with the hashtag #MetGala to uplift this moment. 🎞 by @mylescartuh with thanks to @hennessymg & @dragonflyneptunite for amplifying 

 “By Any Means Necessary” is not just a chant you scream at a parade. It is a call-to-action that my comrade, my sibling, my DAUGHTA, Ella understood. Ella and my fellow comrades uplifted over a year of Black Activism and the spread of Abolitionist Teachings through this historic demonstration. These are the next steps…. educating by any means necessary, looking the oppressor in the face and holding your ground. If we allow them to erase our power, we allow them to erase all of us.

We are doing a mass spam using the #metgala #metgala2021 so that the people blinded by capitalism and ignorance, ESPECIALLY THE “CELEBRITIES,” are aware that Black Lives still matter and Black People will remain a priority.” 

#BlackLivesMatter #MetGala2021 #BlackTransLiveMatter

Quannah Chasinghorse, (@quannah.rose) indigenous activist, model and land protector showed what American beauty truly is, where it started and represented the indigenous community at the #MetGala2021.

“Quannah Chasinghorse, whose Indigenous ancestry is both Hän Gwich’in (from Alaska and Canada) and Oglala Lakota (from South Dakota)—rarely saw her culture represented in the fashion she voraciously consumed. “I was obsessed with watching runway shows on television—Dior, Chanel, Prada—and I was always posing for pictures,” she says, but because of this lack of representation, “it was really hard for me to feel like I had the potential to be a model.”
“Fast-forward a few years, though, and Chasinghorse, 19 and now living in and working from Fairbanks, Alaska, is one of modeling’s freshest new faces. Chasinghorse is breaking barriers in an industry that has long overlooked Indigenous talent. Armed with her traditional Hän Gwich’in tattoos, the model is at once redefining beauty, honoring a Native practice dating back more than 10,000 years, and challenging the notion that all models should be a blank canvas.” Source @vogue

@quannah.rose wore Diné silver and turquoise jewelry from Miss Navajo Nation 2006 @JocelynBillyUpshaw made by artists in the south west.

node.text:
10 things you can say “yes” to today:
💭 by @morganharpernichols

1
Spending more time with the people who energize you

2
Spending time doing nothing at all, and not feeling bad about it

3
Scheduling more time for you to do something you enjoy, no matter how small it is

4
Not having to have an explanation for why you're saying "no" to something

5
Doing things that would make your childhood self filled with joy

6
Doing things that would make your 90-year-old self smile

7
Getting an extra hour of sleep

8
Taking some much-needed time off

9
Just seeing where the present moment in a quiet space leads you

10
Continuing to become who you were meant to be, regardless of the pressures you feel from the world

MHN

Via @19thnews “On the easternmost corner of ground zero on the afternoon of September 11, 2001, Brenda Berkman and a small group of her fellow firefighters stood before a wall of flames and dust.⁠
⁠
She never watched the media coverage of the attacks in the weeks that followed. So she was surprised when she started getting phone calls from other women firefighters she knew across the country. ⁠
⁠
What is going on in New York? they asked her. There were no women — not just women firefighters, but no women first responders at all — in the coverage of the day, though they knew women, including Berkman, had been there. ⁠
⁠
The focus of the coverage at the time was on the heroism of the firemen and policemen. Women were only spotlighted as widows or nurses, another example of how women are often erased from history, Berkman said.⁠
⁠
But she wasn’t sure how she could broach the subject. At the time, there was a culture of unity among the 9/11 first responders. Criticizing might be deemed unpatriotic. ⁠
⁠
But, she remembers thinking: “What’s more patriotic than to point out that everyone in the United States, including the women and people of color and LGBT community, that they’re all doing the right thing — everyone is pulling together, everyone is making sacrifices?” Berkman, 69, told The 19th ahead of the 20th anniversary of 9/11. ⁠
⁠
In the years since she retired as a captain in 2006, much of Berkman’s work has been consumed by ensuring that women continue to be part of the narrative — the true narrative — of what really happened that day on ground zero.⁠
⁠
